recordings.file-name: FIELD SPARROW chip calls Palmyra NJ 7406(1).mp3

recordings.rmk: This is an unfortunately noisy cut, but is a good demonstration of the sometimes-similar songs of Field Sparrow and Prairie Warbler. In areas that may not seem like "good FISP habitat," if the ending of the song is not heard well, it can be tempting to ID it as PRAW. This is true in upland areas with fairly large openings and a scrubby understory: not flat, not wide-open, not pastures/fields, but still suitable for a FISP. Again, the rising first 2/3 of the song can be quite buzzy-sounding, much like PRAW, but FISP will almost invariably space out the end into a slower, descending series of whistles (the "ping-pong ball coming to rest"), while PRAW usually finishes with up-slurred, buzzing phrases.

The closest I can come to an ID for this song is Field Sparrow, but in none of the recordings I have heard does the song slow back down after the trill.
Habitat is bordering open grassland, and the bird made a brief appearance high in a tree when I tried to imitate the call. It was at a great distance and backlit, but I could make out a light breast and notched tail.
The recording is amplified.
Thanks for any help!

Other notes were that the first part of the song is rather reminiscent of Hooded Warbler as well as the last descending note. Recorded by a birding friend of mine, Barbara Sherman on an iPhone 5s. Singing frequency about once a minute, habitat was successional pine forest (a power lines area), singing from fairly high up, possibly at the treetops. Conditions: Sunny, 80 degrees F.

Unmodified recording from small Sony digital recorder, song at about 0:04 and 0:19; open short woodland with lots of cedars and osage orange, adjoining rural mowed yard; bird was singing from tree tops and was only glimpsed briefly and distant flying from one singing location to another.  Sounded more like Spotted Towhee which would be unusual for area in summer, but clear start and following trill did not sound quite like either Eastern or Spotted.  Spectrogram done in Raven Lite didn't look enough like specs for a variety of Easterns or Spotteds, but I can't think what else would sing like that.

recordings.rmk: Both Field Sparrow and Carolina Wren are prominent in the cut
